iometrics, and post-9/11 airport security practices. Surveillance, Browne asserts, is both a discursive and material practice that reifies boundaries, borders, and bodies around racial lines, so much so that the surveillance of blackness has long been, and continues to be, a social and political norm.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aBlackszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aElectronic surveillancezUnited States. 0aGovernment informationzUnited States. 4aLora Romero prize. 4aMcGannon Award Winner. 4aRomero Winner. 4aSurveillance Studies Network book award. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375302zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375302.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles